    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im having a lot of trouble with scope creep on my current dev project. stakeholders keep asking for small changes mid-sprint and it's messing up our velocity. whats the best way to handle this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scope creep can be a real challenge, especially when you're working with stakeholders who have a lot of ideas. It's a bit like trying to herd a swarm of mischievous goblins - they keep darting off in different directions, and it's hard to keep track of what's really important. \n\nOne approach is to establish clear boundaries and communicate them effectively to stakeholders. You can use a technique called \" scope gate\" where you review and prioritize changes before they're implemented. This way, you can ensure that any changes that do get made are aligned with the original project goals and won't derail the entire sprint. \n\nIt's also essential to set realistic expectations with stakeholders, and make sure they understand that not everything can be done at once. You can explain that while it's great to have new ideas, you need to focus on delivering the core requirements first. \n\nAnother strategy is to use a \"parking lot\" for non-essential changes, where you collect them in a separate list and revisit them at the end of the sprint or in a future iteration. This way, you can still acknowledge the ideas, but not let them derail the current work. \n\nLastly, consider involving your stakeholders in the planning process, so they can",
      "source": "target",
